{{other people}} {{Infobox serial killer |name = Thomas Dillon |image = Thomas_Dillon.jpg |caption = Thomas Lee Dillon |alias = |birth_date = {{Birth date|1950|7|9}} |birth_place = [[Canton, Ohio]], U.S. |death_date = {{death date and age|2011|10|21|1950|7|9}} |death_place = [[Columbus, Ohio]], U.S. |victims = 5 known |country = U.S. |states = [[Ohio]] |beginyear = April 1, 1989 |endyear = April 5, 1992 |apprehended = November 27, 1992 |penalty = * 5 terms of 30 years to life for [[aggravated murder]] * 15 years additional for gun specification |weapons = .308 Mauser rifle, 6.5 x 55mm Mauser Rifle }}
'''Thomas Lee Dillon''' (July 9, 1950<ref name="offender">[http://www.drc.state.oh.us/OffenderSearch/Details.aspx?id=A277618&pg=x Dillon profile at the Ohio Department of Rehabilitation and Correction]</ref><ref name="weird">Willis, James A., Andrew Henderson and Loren Coleman. [https://books.google.com/books?id=BYHK2lN5KzoC&pg=PA108 ''Weird Ohio: Your Travel Guide to Ohio's Local Legends and Best Kept Secrets'', "Ohio's Unsportsmanlike Sniper", pp. 108-110]. Sterling Publishing Co., Ltd. 2005.</ref> – October 21, 2011) was an American [[serial killer]] who shot and killed five men in southeastern [[Ohio]], beginning April 1, 1989 and continuing until April 1992.<ref name="cbs">{{cite web|last=Kohn|first=David|title=A Sniper's Mind|work=CBSNEWS.com|publisher=CBS News|date=February 11, 2009|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2002/10/23/60II/main526716.shtml|accessdate=August 30, 2017 }}</ref>
==Life and crimes== {{more citations needed|section|date=August 2017}} Dillon was born in [[Canton, Ohio]] and was a resident of nearby [[Magnolia, Ohio|Magnolia]]. He had a wife and son and was employed for twelve years as a [[draftsman]] at the [[Canton, Ohio|Canton Ohio]] Waterworks.
Between the period of April 1, 1989 to April 5, 1992, Dillon shot and killed five people in Ohio. His fourth victim, Claude Hawkins, was shot on [[Federal lands|federal property]] and was the reason the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] stepped in to join the investigation along with officers from the other three counties and the [[Ohio Department of Natural Resources]]. It was after this that the death of Kevin Loring was changed from an accident to a homicide.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}
Ten days after the [[task force]] meeting, Dillon would shoot his fifth victim, Gary Bradley, in [[Noble County, Ohio]]. Dillon was placed under surveillance in 1992 when a friend reported him after hearing the task force's initial press release concerning the murders. Larry Oller of [[Barnhill, Ohio]] was later shot at by Dillon while out hunting in [[Tuscarawas County, Ohio|Tuscarawas County]], but he escaped uninjured.
== Arrest == Dillon was arrested on a weapons charge on November 27, 1992, and he was placed under probation for owning a [[suppressor]].{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}
After the death penalty was removed as an option for punishment, Dillon admitted to the killings. On July 12, 1993 at the [[Noble County Courthouse (Ohio)|Noble County Courthouse]], Dillon pleaded guilty to the five murders. Dillon was incarcerated at the [[Southern Ohio Correctional Facility]] for five [[consecutive sentence]]s of thirty years to life for [[aggravated murder]].<ref name="offender"/>
After an attempt by Dillon's wife to sell Dillon's story to Hollywood, Jean Paxton, Jamie Paxton's mother, and Ohio State Senator [[Bob Ney]], passed the Paxton Bill, which barred killers or their relatives from profiting from their crimes.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}
==Victims== Dillon's shooting victims were:<ref name="Times Reporter">{{cite web|last=Morrison|first=Lee|title=Hunter murderer Thomas Lee Dillon dies at 61|work=TimesReporter.com|publisher=The Times Reporter|date=October 23, 2011|url=http://www.timesreporter.com/communities/coshocton/x464391936/Hunter-murderer-Thomas-Lee-Dillon-dies-at-61|accessdate=August 30, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120424232944/http://www.timesreporter.com/communities/coshocton/x464391936/Hunter-murderer-Thomas-Lee-Dillon-dies-at-61|archivedate=April 24, 2012}}</ref>
* Donald Welling, 35, of [[Strasburg, Ohio]] on April 1, 1989, while walking or jogging on [[Tuscarawas County, Ohio|Tuscarawas County]] Road 94. * Jamie Paxton, 21, of [[Bannock, Ohio]] on Nov. 10, 1990, while deer hunting in [[Belmont County, Ohio|Belmont County]]. * Kevin Loring, 30, of [[Duxbury, Massachusetts|Duxbury, Mass.]] on Nov. 28, 1990, while deer hunting in [[Muskingum County]]. * Claude Hawkins, 48, of [[Mansfield, Ohio]] on March 14, 1992, while fishing at [[Wills Creek (Ohio)|Wills Creek dam]] in [[Coshocton County, Ohio|Coshocton County]]. * Gary Bradley, 44, of [[Williamstown, West Virginia]], on April 5, 1992, while fishing in [[Caldwell, Ohio]] in [[Noble County, Ohio|Noble County]].
Dillon was also investigated in connection with the unsolved shooting death of John Joseph Harvat on November 28, 1984, at a hunting camp in [[Wetmore Township, McKean County, Pennsylvania]]. In 1993, officials in Coshocton County notified the Pennsylvania State Police that Dillon had been named a suspect in several similar shootings in Ohio, but Dillon refused to discuss Harvat's case with police.<ref name="crimestoppers">{{cite web|title=Media Release #2282, Suspicious Death of John Joseph Harvat – Wetmore Township, McKean County, PA|publisher=Pennsylvania Crime Stoppers|date=July 6, 2018|url=https://www.crimewatchpa.com/crimestoppers/316/cases/media-release-2282-suspicious-death-john-joseph-harvat-%E2%80%93-wetmore-township-mckean-county-pa|accessdate=July 9, 2018}}</ref>
==Death==
On October 21, 2011, Dillon died in the prison wing at Corrections Medical Center in [[Columbus, Ohio]], aged 61, after being ill for nearly three weeks due to an unspecified illness.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ludlow|first=Randy|title=Killer Dillon, who hunted outdoorsmen, is dead|work=The Columbus Dispatch|date=October 22, 2011|url=http://www.dispatch.com/content/stories/local/2011/10/22/killer-dillon-who-hunted-outdoorsmen-is-dead.html|accessdate=August 30, 2017}}</ref>
